        'source_url' => 'https://sugbo.ph/2023/travel-guide-bantayan/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Sugbo.ph',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Bantayan Island Weekend: A Sta. Fe Plan That Actually Rests',
        'slug' => 'bantayan-island-weekend-sta-fe-plan',
        'excerpt' => 'Bantayan is the calm Cebu weekend a lot of travelers forget about. Here is how to do Sta. Fe and the smaller beaches in two days without overbooking.',
        'content_html' => '<p>Bantayan is the part of Cebu that earned its reputation by staying quiet. The island sits off the northern tip of Cebu, around four hours from the city by bus and ferry, and rewards travelers who want a beach weekend without the Mactan crowd. Sta. Fe is the main jump-off town, and most of the powdery beach you came for is within a 10-minute tricycle ride from the port.</p><p>This plan covers a Friday-night arrival, a full Saturday, and a Sunday afternoon trip back. Realistic for a Manila or Cebu City office worker who wants the kwento of a real island weekend.</p><h2>Getting to Bantayan</h2><p>From Cebu City, ride a Grab or metered taxi to the North Bus Terminal near SM City. Look for the direct Ceres or Ceres-Bantayan bus bound for Hagnaya Port in San Remigio. The bus fare is around 200 pesos and travel time is around 3 hours. The RORO ferry from Hagnaya to Sta. Fe takes a little over an hour and runs hourly through the day.</p><h3>If You Are Flying In</h3><p>From Manila, take an early flight to Mactan-Cebu. <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> and Philippine Airlines both run early-morning slots that line up with the noon ferry from Hagnaya. Land by 9 a.m., taxi straight to the bus terminal, and you will be on the island by sunset.</p><h2>Friday Night: Settle and Eat</h2><p>Most travelers arrive in Sta. Fe by mid-afternoon to early evening. Drop your bags, walk to MJ Square for dinner. The square is a cluster of small carinderias and bars about 15 minutes on foot from the port. Order the grilled liempo and fresh fish, the catch comes in the same day.</p><h2>Saturday: Beach and Slow Island Hopping</h2><p>Wake up to the sunrise on the east-facing beach, then ride a tricycle to Paradise Beach for the morning. Paradise is a 10-minute ride from town and the sand is finer here than in front of most hotels. There is a small entrance fee paid at the gate.</p><h3>Afternoon Island Hopping</h3><p>For lunch and the afternoon, book an island-hopping boat from Sta. Fe pier. The standard loop covers Virgin Island, Hilantagaan Island, and Kota Beach for snorkeling and a beach lunch. Boats leave around 10 a.m. and return by 3 p.m. Coordinate with your boatman in the morning, prices fluctuate by season and group size.</p><h3>Sunset and Dinner</h3><p>Back at Sta. Fe, walk the beachfront for sunset. The sky over the strait is one of those calm island sunsets that you do not need a filter for. Dinner is again at MJ Square or one of the beachfront seafood places near Kota Beach Resort.</p><h2>Sunday: Slow Morning, Then Sail</h2><p>Take a slow breakfast at one of the cafes near the church plaza, then walk through Sta. Fe town proper. The old Bantayan church in the town center is one of the oldest in the country, and the public market is worth a 30-minute browse for dried fish and pasalubong.</p><p>Catch the early afternoon ferry back to Hagnaya, then the bus to Cebu City. You will be back in the city by sunset, sun-tired and slightly salty.</p><h2>What to Pack</h2><ul><li>Reef-safe sunscreen, the marine sanctuaries are strict</li><li>Cash, ATMs in town are limited and sometimes offline</li><li>A light rashguard for snorkeling, the sun is sharp at noon</li><li>A book or two, the beach calls for slow reading</li><li>Sandals you can wade in</li></ul><p>For where to sleep, the cluster around Sta. Fe and the quieter stretch toward Kota Beach both work. You can cross-check listings on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g676399-Bantayan_Island_Cebu_Island_Visayas-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Beachfront is the move if it is your first time. Inland inns are calmer if you have already been.</p><p>Bantayan is one of those Cebu trips that holds up because it does not chase trends. Move slow, eat the grilled fish hot, and let the island do its thing.</p><p class="source-credit"><em>Inspired by and adapted from <a href="https://sugbo.ph/2023/travel-guide-bantayan/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Sugbo.ph</a>.</em></p>',
        'meta_title' => 'Bantayan Island Weekend Guide from Cebu | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm two-day Bantayan plan from Cebu City, covering Sta. Fe, Paradise Beach, island hopping, and the ferry route through Hagnaya Port.',
        'tags' => 'Cebu, Bantayan, weekend, beach, Sta Fe, Visayas',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'cebu-city',
