    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.thepoortraveler.net/2017/03/malapascua-island-itinerary-guide/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'The Poor Traveler',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Malapascua and the Thresher Sharks: A DIY Diving Plan',
        'slug' => 'malapascua-thresher-sharks-diving-plan',
        'excerpt' => 'Malapascua is the small Cebu island where you can see thresher sharks at dawn. Here is how to plan the trip from Cebu City without rushing the dive prep.',
        'content_html' => '<p>Malapascua is the kind of dive trip that rewards the early riser. The thresher sharks come up from the deep before sunrise to visit the cleaning stations at Monad and Kimud Shoal, and the boats leave the island before the first light. If you are not in the water by 6 a.m., you missed the dive.</p><p>This is a small island in northern Cebu, just off the coast of Daanbantayan, and the trip from Cebu City takes most of the day by bus and outrigger. Plan for a minimum of three nights to make the dives worth the transit.</p><h2>Getting There from Cebu City</h2><p>Take a taxi or Grab to the Cebu North Bus Terminal near SM City. Ride the bus bound for Maya Port in Daanbantayan, the fare is around 220 pesos and the trip takes around four hours with stops. Time the bus so you reach Maya by mid-afternoon, the last outrigger to Malapascua usually leaves before sunset.</p><h3>The Banca Ride</h3><p>From Maya Port, a small public outrigger crosses to Malapascua in around 30 to 45 minutes. There is also a private hire if you missed the last public boat. Most dive resorts will coordinate the pickup if you let them know your bus arrival time.</p><h2>The Thresher Shark Dive</h2><p>Monad Shoal sits about 30 minutes east of Malapascua. Thresher sharks have visited the cleaning stations there for decades, and although the population shifted in recent years toward nearby Kimud Shoal, the dawn dive is still the main draw. Sightings are not guaranteed, but the success rate across multiple operators stays high.</p><h3>What to Expect on the Dive</h3><p>The boat leaves the island around 5 a.m., usually still dark. You gear up on the way out and descend to around 20 to 25 meters at first light. The thresher sharks move slowly through the water, long-tailed and graceful, and the dive ends after around 35 minutes because of the depth.</p><h3>Other Dive Sites Worth Adding</h3><p>Gato Island has a swim-through tunnel with sleeping white-tip sharks. Lapus Lapus and Lighthouse have softer coral and macro life. If you have an open-water certification, ask your dive shop to mix in a sunset dive at Lighthouse for the mandarinfish.</p><h2>Where to Stay</h2><p>Bounty Beach is the main strip and has most of the dive shops, small inns, and casual restaurants. Logon village on the south side is quieter and has the small chapel and the old well. For listings of dive-friendly inns, you can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g664709-Malapascua_Island_Cebu_Island_Visayas-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p><h2>What to Pack</h2><ul><li>Your dive certification card and logbook</li><li>Personal mask if you have one, rentals fit unevenly</li><li>A surface marker buoy if you have it</li><li>Cash, the island has limited ATMs</li><li>A warm layer for the early-morning boat ride</li></ul><h2>Getting to Cebu and Back</h2><p>Direct flights to Mactan-Cebu run hourly from Manila. <a href="https://www.philippineairlines.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Philippine Airlines</a> and Cebu Pacific both fly the route. Plan an early arrival on day one so you can catch the bus to Maya without panic, and a late afternoon flight out on the last day so you can make the boat-to-bus connection without rushing.</p><p>Malapascua is one of those Philippine dive trips that holds its shape because the island stayed small. Respect the cleaning stations, dive with a licensed operator, and you will leave with a kwento that beats most island-hopping days.</p><p class="source-credit"><em>Inspired by and adapted from <a href="https://www.thepoortraveler.net/2017/03/malapascua-island-itinerary-guide/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">The Poor Traveler</a>.</em></p>',
        'meta_title' => 'Malapascua Thresher Shark Diving DIY Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm DIY guide to diving with thresher sharks at Monad Shoal in Malapascua. Bus route from Cebu City, dawn dive prep, and other sites worth adding.',
        'tags' => 'Cebu, Malapascua, diving, thresher shark, Visayas',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'cebu-city',
    ],
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.rjdexplorer.com/moalboal-itinerary/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'RJ Dexplorer',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Moalboal Sardine Run: A Slow Snorkel Day at Panagsama',
        'slug' => 'moalboal-sardine-run-slow-snorkel-panagsama',
        'excerpt' => 'The sardine run at Panagsama is one of the rare year-round snorkel scenes in the country. Here is the calm way to do it from Cebu City as a day trip or overnight.',
        'content_html' => '<p>Moalboal is one of the easiest snorkeling trips in the Philippines because the sardines do most of the work. The schools live just 20 to 30 meters off Panagsama Beach, at depths shallow enough for an unhurried freedive. You walk down the steps, kick out past the reef edge, and the silver wall moves around you. It is a calm experience if you let it be.</p><p>The town sits on the southwest coast of Cebu, around three hours by bus from Cebu City, and pairs well with a Kawasan canyoneering day if you have the time.</p><h2>Getting There</h2><p>From Cebu City, ride a Grab to the South Bus Terminal and take a Ceres bus bound for Bato via Barili. Bus fare is around 150 to 200 pesos and travel time is around three hours. Tell the conductor to drop you at the Moalboal junction, then ride a tricycle for around 15 minutes down to Panagsama.</p><h3>For Day Trippers</h3><p>It is doable as a long day from Cebu City if you leave by 5 a.m. and head back by 4 p.m. But the better plan is to stay one night, snorkel at dawn the next morning when the sardines come in tighter, then catch the late bus back.</p><h2>The Snorkel Itself</h2><p>Panagsama Beach is not a swimming beach in the usual sense. The shoreline is rocky and has dive shops along the cliff edge, and most snorkelers enter the water from the wooden steps fronting the dive resorts. Kick out 20 to 30 meters, look down, and the sardines should appear at around 5 to 10 meters depth.</p><h3>What You Will See</h3><p>The school is dense enough that the water darkens when they swirl together. Sea turtles also frequent the same reef edge, and you will likely see one or two on a calm morning. The visibility holds best from November to May, dry season, when there is less runoff from the hills.</p><h3>Snorkel Rental</h3><p>Most dive shops along the strip rent snorkel sets for around 100 to 150 pesos per use. Bring your own mask if you have a prescription pair, the rental fit is hit or miss. There is no entrance fee for the sardine run itself, you swim from the public access.</p><h2>What to Pack</h2><ul><li>Reef-safe sunscreen with zinc oxide, the bay is strict</li><li>A rashguard, the open-water sun gets sharp by 9 a.m.</li><li>Water shoes for the rocky shoreline</li><li>A dry bag for your phone</li><li>Cash, the dive shops are not always card-friendly</li></ul><h2>Pair It With a Second Day</h2><p>If you stay two nights, day one is the sardine run and an afternoon trip out to White Beach in Basdaku for the soft sand. Day two is Kawasan canyoneering in nearby Badian or a dive at Pescador Island. Most dive shops on the strip can book either.</p><h2>Where to Stay</h2><p>The Panagsama strip has clusters of small dive-shop inns and beach hostels. Basdaku is quieter and more family-friendly if you want a swim-friendly shore. For options, you can compare listings on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g303872-Moalboal_Cebu_Island_Visayas-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p><h2>Getting to Cebu</h2><p>From Manila, fly into Mactan-Cebu with <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a>, then transit to the South Bus Terminal. Direct flights run hourly.</p><p>Moalboal is one of those Cebu trips where the highlight reel does not need editing. Move slow, breathe deep underwater, and let the sardines fill the frame.</p><p class="source-credit"><em>Inspired by and adapted from <a href="https://www.rjdexplorer.com/moalboal-itinerary/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">RJ Dexplorer</a>.</em></p>',
        'meta_title' => 'Moalboal Sardine Run Snorkel Guide | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm DIY snorkel plan for the sardine run at Panagsama Beach in Moalboal, with bus route from Cebu City and tips on pairing it with Kawasan canyoneering.',
        'tags' => 'Cebu, Moalboal, sardine run, snorkeling, Panagsama, Visayas',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'cebu-city',
